ree case studies, that involve economic redevelopment, historic preservation, and redistricting in San Diego, New York, and Los Angeles, Saito illustrates the enduring presence of racial considerations and inequality in public policy. Individuals and groups who may sincerely characterize themselves as free of racial prejudice still participate, though perhaps unwittingly, in practices that have racialized outcomes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150362720840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503627208423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503627208/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles